    outlook: "So, what happens next? For SpaceX, the immediate focus will be on executing its ambitious roadmap. The company has already earmarked $15 billion from the IPO proceeds for Starship development, with the first crewed lunar mission slated for 2028. Starlink’s expansion into Africa and Southeast Asia could add another 2 million subscribers by 2027, while the launch of its second-generation satellites (Gen2) will double its network capacity.\n\nOn the regulatory front, SpaceX will need to navigate the FCC’s new rules on satellite constellations, which could slow Starlink’s growth in key markets. The company is also bracing for a legal battle with Amazon over orbital slots, a dispute that could drag on for years.\n\nFor investors, the next six months will be critical. Analysts expect SpaceX’s stock to trade between $180 and $220, with a potential pullback if profit-taking sets in. The first earnings call in August will be closely watched for updates on Starship’s progress and Starlink’s churn rate. \"If SpaceX can hit its 2026 revenue targets, we could see the stock test $250 by year-end,\" said Kapoor. \"But if Starship faces another setback, all bets are off.\"\n\nLong-term, the biggest catalyst will be SpaceX’s Mars ambitions. The company has already sold $500 million in \"Mars tickets\" to private citizens, with the first mission tentatively scheduled for 2030. If successful, it could open up an entirely new revenue stream—interplanetary tourism—and cement SpaceX’s place in history as the first company to make humanity multiplanetary.",
    conclusion: "SpaceX’s IPO isn’t just a financial milestone—it’s a paradigm shift. For the first time, the public can invest in a company that’s not just exploring space but commercializing it. The $250 billion valuation may seem lofty, but it reflects the market’s belief in SpaceX’s ability to dominate the next frontier. Whether that belief is justified will depend on execution, competition, and a bit of cosmic luck.\n\nOne thing is certain: the space economy is no longer science fiction. It’s big business, and SpaceX is leading the charge. As the stock market’s newest darling, the company will face unprecedented scrutiny, but if history is any guide, Elon Musk thrives under pressure. The question isn’t whether SpaceX can live up to the hype—it’s whether the rest of the world is ready for what comes next.",
