    risks: ["**Regulatory Uncertainty**: Starlink faces increasing scrutiny from global regulators over spectrum allocation and light pollution concerns.", "**Competition**: Amazon’s Project Kuiper and China’s satellite internet initiative could erode Starlink’s market share and margins.", "**Technological Risks**: Starship’s success is far from guaranteed, and any setbacks could delay NASA contracts and commercial missions."],
    opportunities: ["**Starlink Expansion**: With only 3 million subscribers, Starlink has massive room for growth, particularly in emerging markets.", "**Starship Commercialization**: If successful, Starship could drastically reduce the cost of space travel, opening up new revenue streams from lunar missions and beyond.", "**Government Contracts**: SpaceX is well-positioned to win more NASA and Department of Defense contracts, providing stable, long-term revenue."],
    outlook: "### What Happens Next?\n\nSpaceX’s IPO is just the beginning. Here’s what to watch in the coming months:\n\n1. **First Earnings Report (Q3 2026)**: Investors will be laser-focused on Starlink’s subscriber growth and Starship’s progress. Any hiccups could send the stock tumbling.\n2. **Regulatory Battles**: Expect more scrutiny from the FCC and international regulators, particularly around Starlink’s spectrum usage and Starship’s environmental impact.\n3. **Competition Heats Up**: Amazon’s Project Kuiper and China’s satellite internet initiative will ramp up their efforts, putting pressure on Starlink’s margins.\n4. **Musk’s Moves**: Will the CEO’s attention remain on SpaceX, or will his other ventures (Tesla, X, Neuralink) distract from the company’s goals?\n5. **Follow-On Offerings**: SpaceX could raise additional capital post-IPO to fund Starship’s development and expand Starlink’s global footprint.\n\nThe next 12 months will be critical for SpaceX. If the company can deliver on its promises—expanding Starlink, perfecting Starship, and securing more government contracts—it could cement its place as the dominant player in the space economy. If not, the stock could face a reckoning, leaving investors to question whether the hype was justified.",
    conclusion: "SpaceX’s market debut is more than just another IPO—it’s a bet on the future of humanity. For the first time, everyday investors have the chance to own a piece of the company that’s making space travel cheaper, satellite internet ubiquitous, and Mars colonization a tangible goal. But with great opportunity comes great risk. SpaceX operates in an industry where failure is a constant threat, and its valuation assumes nothing short of world-changing success.\n\nFor those willing to take the leap, the rewards could be astronomical. For the cautious, the wait-and-see approach might be the smarter play. Either way, one thing is clear: SpaceX’s IPO is set to be the most talked-about financial event of the year. When the stock starts trading on June 25, the world won’t just be watching—it’ll be holding its breath.",
    sourcesReferenced: ["SpaceX S-1 Filing (SEC)", "Morgan Stanley Aerospace Report (June 2026)", "NASA Artemis Program Contracts", "Starlink Quarterly Earnings (2025)"],
    aiAnalysis: null,
